<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-10">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-green-800">Photographing Wildlife Like a Pro</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">By Jungle Pulse Kenya · March 29, 2025</p>

    <img src="/images/wildlife-photography.jpg" alt="Photographing Wildlife" class="rounded-2xl shadow-lg mb-8 w-full">

    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
            Capturing wildlife in its natural habitat requires patience, skill, and the right equipment. In this blog
            post, we'll share practical tips to help you photograph wildlife like a professional—even if you're just
            starting out!
        </p>

        <h2>1. Know Your Subject</h2>
        <p>
            Study the behavior of the animals you want to photograph. The more you understand their movements and
            patterns, the better your chances of capturing the perfect shot.
        </p>

        <h2>2. Invest in the Right Gear</h2>
        <p>
            A DSLR or mirrorless camera with a good zoom lens is ideal. Tripods and monopods help stabilize your shot,
            especially when using longer lenses.
        </p>

        <h2>3. Lighting is Everything</h2>
        <p>
            Early morning and late afternoon provide the best natural lighting. Avoid harsh midday sun if you can.
        </p>

        <h2>4. Practice Patience</h2>
        <p>
            Wildlife photography is about waiting. Sit quietly, blend into the surroundings, and let nature come to you.
        </p>

        <h2>5. Respect Nature</h2>
        <p>
            Never disturb animals for the sake of a photo. Ethical photography means preserving the safety and serenity
            of wildlife.
        </p>

        <h2>Bonus Tip: Go Local</h2>
        <p>
            Kenya has an incredible variety of wildlife right in your backyard. Visit local reserves or join guided
            safaris for amazing opportunities.
        </p>

        <hr>

        <p>
            Got a favorite wildlife shot? Tag us on Instagram with <strong>#JunglePulseKenya</strong> and you might get
            featured!
        </p>
    </div>
</div>